{
  "answer": "In the *Parāśara Smṛti*, the entire text is presented as the authoritative *dharma* (righteous duty) specifically suited to the Kali *yuga* (the present cosmic age), in contrast to the *dharmas* of prior ages.[^1] The duties of a Brāhmaṇa (Brahmin) are enumerated as six core acts to be performed daily, devotion to which ensures one does not perish.[^2] These are:\n\n> Twilight prayers and bathing, recitation of sacred texts (*japa*), fire offerings (*homa*), worship of deities and guests, hospitality to an *atithi* (a guest, who must be honored), and the *Vaiśvadeva* (the daily ritual offering to all deities)—these are the six duties to be performed day by day.[^3]\n\nThese acts are reiterated and elaborated as central to a Brāhmaṇa's householder life in the Kali *yuga*, alongside limited agriculture if needed.[^4]\n\n[^1]: `/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/01/translation/#p-22e02e/`\n[^2]: `/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/01/translation/#p-f4eb93/`\n[^3]: `/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/01/translation/#p-40daa2/`\n[^4]: `/works/unknown-parasara-smrti-2259be/02/translation/`",
